## USER RESEARCH

*(Compiled from TikTok discover pages, nail tech YouTube communities, beauty forum comment patterns, Women & Home reader questions, Paola Ponce Nails community, Femshades beauty forum context, and beauty community FAQs — Reddit inaccessible but community voice captured across these alternatives.)*

### Top 5 Pain Points

1. **"I don't think almond works on short nails"** — The dominant misconception. Readers have been told almond requires length. They see short nails and dismiss the shape before trying it. They need explicit, visual reassurance that short almond is a real, achievable shape — not just a watered-down version of something better.

2. **"I have a wide/flat nail bed — will almond suit me?"** — A deeply felt anxiety about hand flattery. Wide nail beds make people feel the almond taper will look wrong or unbalanced. They want permission and guidance specific to their anatomy, not generic "almond suits everyone" platitudes.

3. **"My nails keep breaking when I file the sides inward"** — A practical fear about the filing process. Especially relevant for natural nail wearers. TikTok discussions and Paola Ponce Nails content confirm this is a real concern — readers are afraid of onycholysis (nail plate lifting) from improper technique.

4. **"I work with my hands / type all day — are shorter almonds actually practical?"** — A lifestyle tension. The reader loves the aesthetic but has real-world anxiety about maintenance, breakage, and functionality. They need direct confirmation that short almond is the shape for people who actually use their hands.

5. **"I don't know what designs or colours work on a shorter length"** — Design confidence gap. Readers assume short nails limit their options. They want specific, 2026-relevant guidance on what works — not just "anything goes." Micro French, milky sheers, soft chrome, and velvet cat-eye are the answers they're not finding clearly articulated together.

### User Sentiment
Aspirational but quietly doubtful — the reader wants the shape to work for her; she just needs someone to prove it will.

